The main difference between `StreamWriter` and `FileWriter` lies in how they handle large amounts of data.
    `FileWriter` reads the entire dataset into memory before writing it to the file, which can be inefficient for large datasets. On the other hand, `StreamWriter` writes data directly to the file without loading it into memory.

    Here is an example demonstrating the difference:

    ```java
import java.io.FileWriter;
import java.io.IOException;
import java.io.PrintWriter;

public class StreamWriterVsFileWriter {
  public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {
    int rows = 100000;
    String data = "";

    // Using FileWriter (inefficient)
    long startTime = System.currentTimeMillis();
    try (FileWriter writer = new FileWriter("output.txt")) {
      for (int i = 0; i < rows; i++) {
        data += "Row " + (i + 1) + "\n";
        writer.write(data);
      }
    } catch (IOException e) {
      System.err.println(e.getMessage());
    }

    long endTime = System.currentTimeMillis();
    System.out.println("Time taken using FileWriter: " + (endTime - startTime) / 1000.0 + " seconds");

    // Using Streamwriter
    startTime = System.currentTimeMillis();
    try (PrintWriter writer = new PrintWriter(new FileWriter("output2.txt"))) {
      for (int i = 0; i < rows; i++) {
        data += "Row " + (i + 1) + "\n";
        writer.println(data);
      }
    } catch (IOException e) {
      System.err.println(e.getMessage());
    }

    endTime = System.currentTimeMillis();
    System.out.println("Time taken using Streamwriter: " + (endTime - startTime) / 1000.0 + " seconds");
  }
}
```

    As you can see, `StreamWriter` is significantly faster for large amounts of data.

    Best practice: Always use `StreamWriter` or other streaming methods when writing large datasets to a file.
    Common pitfall to avoid: Not considering the performance implications of using `FileWriter` for large datasets.
