A graceful shutdown is an essential feature for any production-ready application. It involves cleanly shutting down the application's resources, handling any outstanding requests or connections, and ensuring minimal data loss.

    In Java, you can use a `Thread.UncaughtExceptionHandler` to catch the SIGTERM signal and perform a clean shutdown:

    ```java
    import java.lang.Thread;
    import java.util.concurrent.ExecutorService;

    public class ShutdownHandler {
      private ExecutorService executor = Executors.newSingleThreadExecutor();

      public void startApplication() {
        executor.submit(this::handleRequest);
      }

      private void httpRequest() {
        // Handle HTTP requests
      }

      @Override
      public void uncaughtException(Thread t, Throwable e) {
        if (e instanceof InterruptedException) {
          System.out.println("Caught Interrupted Exception: " + e.getMessage());
          shutdown();
        } else {
          System.out.println("Caught Uncaught Exception: " + e.getMessage());
        }
      }

      private void shutdown() {
        executor.shutdown();
        try {
          while (!executor.isTerminated()) {
            Thread.sleep(100);
          }
        } catch (InterruptedException ex) {
          Thread.currentThread().interrupt();
        }
      }
    }
    |

