The External Sort implementation is a optimization technique used to improve the performance of queries that involve sorting large datasets on disk. It works by dividing the data into smaller chunks, sorting each chunk individually, and then recombining the sorted chunks to produce the final sorted result.

    ```code
// Example of External Sort implementation in C#
public class ExternalSort {
  public void sort(long[] arr) {
    int n = arr.length;
    // Divide the array into smaller chunks
    int chunkSize = 10000;
    int[] chunks = new int[n / chunkSize];
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i += chunkSize) {
      chunks[i / chunkSize] = new long[chunkSize];
      System.arraycopy(arr, i, chunks[i / chunkSize], 0, chunkSize);
    }

    // Sort each chunk individually
    for (int i = 0; i < chunks.length; i++) {
      Arrays.sort(chunks[i]);
    }

    // Recombine the sorted chunks
    long[] result = new long[n];
    int j = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i += chunkSize) {
      for (int k = 0; k < chunkSize; k++) {
        result[i + k] = chunks[j][k];
      }
      j++;
    }

    // Copy the sorted result back to the original array
    System.arraycopy(result, 0, arr, 0, n);
  }
}
```
    |

    Best practices for using External Sort include: 
    - Using a suitable chunk size that balances performance and memory usage. 
    - Ensuring sufficient memory is allocated for sorting each chunk to avoid loading data into RAM unnecessarily.
    - Handling edge cases such as empty arrays or arrays with single elements.

    Common pitfalls to avoid:
    - Not considering the trade-off between time and space complexity, leading to inefficient use of resources.
    - Failing to account for disk I/O overhead when estimating query performance.

    Related concepts include:
